Your Honor,

I stand before this court today as a self-represented defendant, Chloe Mills, pleading guilty to the offense of affray. I acknowledge my actions on the night of the incident and take full responsibility for them.

On that night, I found myself confronted with the devastating news of my boyfriend's infidelity. Overwhelmed by emotions and consumed by anger, I made the decision to confront him directly at the bar where he was located. My intention was to seek answers and closure, although I understand now that my approach was deeply flawed.

Upon arrival at the bar, I confess that I allowed my emotions to get the better of me. I engaged in an outburst of yelling and made an ill-advised remark about obtaining a gun, purely to gain insight into the situation. It is important to note that I do not own a gun and had no means of acquiring one. While I regret resorting to such extreme language, I did not pose any actual harm or threat to anyone present.

During the course of the incident, I did slap my boyfriend in the face, an act that I now recognize as inappropriate and regrettable. I acknowledge the disruption and fear that my behavior may have caused to the patrons and staff of the bar. I understand that by resorting to such actions, I failed to handle the situation in a more composed and rational manner.

However, I would like to highlight that this is an isolated incident in my otherwise clean record. I have led a law-abiding life up until this point, which serves as a testament to my character. I have taken the initiative to attend therapy sessions once a week to address my emotional well-being and personal growth.

Recognizing the gravity of my actions, I assure the court that this incident has been a catalyst for personal reflection and growth. I am deeply remorseful for the fear and discomfort I may have caused to others within the bar. It is my sincere hope that by acknowledging my guilt and expressing genuine remorse, I can show the court that I am committed to making amends and becoming a better individual.

In conclusion, I humbly request leniency from the court, taking into consideration my early guilty plea and the mitigating factors present in this case. I understand the weight of my actions and the consequences they carry. I am wholeheartedly committed to learning from this experience, making restitution, and preventing any recurrence of such behavior in the future.

Thank you, Your Honor, for your attention.

